      "rawMarkdown": "## 1. Abound\n\n**Pronunciation:** ə-BOUND\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To exist in large numbers or large quantity.\n**Bangla meaning:** প্রচুর পরিমাণে থাকা, ভরপুর থাকা\n**Root story:** From Latin *abundare*, meaning “to overflow.” Imagine water overflowing from a river.\n**Simple explanation:** If something abounds, there is a lot of it.\n**Memory hook:** **Abound = abundance everywhere.**\n**GRE synonyms:** teem, proliferate, swarm, flourish, overflow\n**Basic synonyms:** be plentiful, be full of, exist widely, be common\n**Antonyms:** lack, be scarce, be rare, disappear\n**Common usage:** opportunities abound, evidence abounds, wildlife abounds, rumors abound\n**Confusing word:** **Abound ≠ Abandon**. Abound = প্রচুর থাকা; abandon = ছেড়ে দেওয়া।\n**Final memory:** **Abound = overflow with quantity = প্রচুর থাকা**\n\n### 10 Examples\n\n1. Fish abound in this river.\n2. Opportunities abound in large cities.\n3. Flowers abound in spring.\n4. Evidence abounds that regular exercise improves health.\n5. Errors abound in the poorly edited report.\n6. Renewable energy resources abound in sunny coastal regions.\n7. In complex engineering projects, constraints abound.\n8. Rumors abounded after the sudden resignation of the minister.\n9. In biodiversity studies, insects often abound in humid forests.\n10. Although data abound, clear interpretation remains difficult.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15 Sentences\n\n1. Mosquitoes **teem** in stagnant water after heavy rain.\n2. The forest **teems** with wildlife.\n3. The report **teems** with statistical errors.\n4. The city **teemed** with visitors during the festival.\n5. The old archive **teems** with forgotten letters.\n6. Online rumors can **proliferate** rapidly after a political crisis.\n7. Small startups began to **proliferate** after the new tax policy.\n8. Misinformation may **proliferate** when official communication is weak.\n9. Factories **proliferated** near the port after trade expanded.\n10. Research papers on artificial intelligence continue to **proliferate**.\n11. Reporters **swarmed** around the official after the announcement.\n12. Complaints **swarmed** the company’s website after the product failed.\n13. Supporters **swarmed** the stadium after the victory.\n14. The market **swarmed** with cheap imitation products.\n15. Questions **swarmed** in his mind before the interview.\n\n---",
