      "rawMarkdown": "## 4. Belie\n\n**Pronunciation:** bih-LY\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To give a false impression; to contradict the truth.\n**Bangla meaning:** মিথ্যা ধারণা দেওয়া, আসল সত্যকে ভুলভাবে দেখানো\n**Root story:** From Old English *beleogan*, meaning “to deceive by lies.”\n**Simple explanation:** If something belies the truth, it makes the truth look different from reality.\n**Memory hook:** **Belie has “lie” inside = false impression.**\n**GRE synonyms:** contradict, negate, disprove, misrepresent, mask\n**Basic synonyms:** hide, conceal, disguise, distort\n**Antonyms:** reveal, confirm, show, prove, expose\n**Common usage:** smile belies sadness, calmness belies fear, appearance belies strength\n**Confusing word:** **Belie ≠ Believe**. Belie = false impression; believe = trust.\n**Final memory:** **Belie = make the truth look false = মিথ্যা ধারণা দেওয়া**\n\n### 10 Examples\n\n1. Her smile belied her sadness.\n2. His calm voice belied his fear.\n3. The old house belied its strong structure.\n4. The company’s confident statement belied its financial problems.\n5. His modest appearance belied his great influence.\n6. The peaceful surface belied the political tension beneath.\n7. The simple graph belied the complexity of the data.\n8. Mild symptoms may belie a serious disease.\n9. Smooth machine operation may belie hidden mechanical fatigue.\n10. National averages can belie regional inequality.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15 Sentences\n\n1. The evidence **contradicted** the witness’s testimony.\n2. His actions **contradicted** his promises.\n3. The new data **contradict** the earlier theory.\n4. Her cheerful tone **contradicted** the seriousness of the news.\n5. The company’s losses **contradicted** its claims of success.\n6. The result **negated** the researcher’s original assumption.\n7. His confession **negated** the need for further speculation.\n8. The discovery **negated** years of accepted belief.\n9. The contract clause **negated** the verbal promise.\n10. One clear fact can **negate** a weak argument.\n11. The DNA evidence **disproved** the accusation.\n12. The experiment **disproved** the popular theory.\n13. The figures **disproved** the minister’s claim.\n14. His calm appearance **masked** deep anxiety.\n15. The official report **misrepresented** the actual conditions.\n\n---",
