      "rawMarkdown": "## 8. Conspicuous\n\n**Pronunciation:** kən-SPIK-yoo-əs\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Easily seen; attracting attention.\n**Bangla meaning:** চোখে পড়ার মতো, সুস্পষ্ট, লক্ষণীয়\n**Root story:** From Latin *conspicere*, meaning “to look at, observe, notice.”\n**Simple explanation:** Something conspicuous stands out clearly.\n**Memory hook:** **Conspicuous = can be spotted quickly.**\n**GRE synonyms:** prominent, noticeable, obvious, salient, striking\n**Basic synonyms:** visible, clear, easy to see\n**Antonyms:** hidden, obscure, inconspicuous, subtle\n**Common usage:** conspicuous absence, conspicuous error, conspicuous success, conspicuous color\n**Confusing word:** **Conspicuous ≠ Suspicious**. Conspicuous = noticeable; suspicious = doubtful.\n**Final memory:** **Conspicuous = easy to notice = চোখে পড়ার মতো**\n\n### 10 Examples\n\n1. His red shirt was conspicuous.\n2. The mistake was conspicuous.\n3. She was conspicuous in the crowd.\n4. The report had a conspicuous lack of evidence.\n5. His absence from the meeting was conspicuous.\n6. The experiment produced a conspicuous change in temperature.\n7. The policy failed because of a conspicuous design flaw.\n8. A conspicuous rise in infection rates demands attention.\n9. Conspicuous cracks may indicate structural risk.\n10. Conspicuous consumption refers to buying things to display status.\n\n### GRE Synonym Examples — 15 Sentences\n\n1. The scientist made a **prominent** contribution to the field.\n2. The scar was **prominent** on his face.\n3. A **prominent** error weakened the paper.\n4. The issue became **prominent** during the debate.\n5. The tower is the most **prominent** structure in the city.\n6. Her nervousness was **noticeable**.\n7. The improvement in performance was **noticeable**.\n8. A **noticeable** gap appeared between rich and poor regions.\n9. The report showed a **noticeable** decline in quality.\n10. His absence was immediately **noticeable**.\n11. The answer was **obvious** after the explanation.\n12. The policy had an **obvious** weakness.\n13. The most **salient** point was the lack of evidence.\n14. The painting’s **striking** colors drew attention.\n15. The experiment produced a **marked** increase in pressure.\n\n---",
